The paper discusses the application of machine learning to travel behavior modeling, which falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also evaluates the performance of the models on stated-preference survey data, which can be considered as a type of consumer behavior analysis (cs.CE). The use of machine learning to capture nonlinear relationships between input features and choice outcomes suggests the relevance of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and social influence (cs.SI) sub-categories. Finally, the paper also discusses the potential for merging ideas from machine learning and conventional statistical methods, which can be related to information theory (cs.IT).
